[3] Cholera - Zambia (Lusaka)
Date: Wed, 28 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail and Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=50863&SelectRegion=Southern_Africa&SelectCountry=ZAMBIA>

Heavy rains have exacerbated a cholera outbreak in Zambia, where at
least 6 people have died and more than 1000 cases have been recorded.
Zambia's ministry of health confirmed on Wed, 28 Dec 2005, that 1144
cases of cholera have been reported since the outbreak began in Aug
2005, with the numbers rising sharply in the last week.
A ministry of health official told IRIN the epidemic was mainly
concentrated in urban areas. "Most of the cholera cases are from [the
capital] Lusaka. Cases are increasing everyday due to the sanitation
and water problems we have at this time of the year [during the rainy
season]," the official noted.
Apart from the 6 confirmed cholera-related deaths, a further 6 deaths
were still to be confirmed.
The health and local government ministries were in crisis talks in a
bid to prevent a repeat of the 2004 cholera epidemic, which claimed
over 100 lives. In 2004, the government closed large markets, such as
Soweto in Lusaka, and restricted movement from areas affected by
cholera.
--
